    "created_at": "2025-02-23T23:18:42Z",
    "updated_at": "2025-02-23T23:18:42Z",
    "body": "> I found an workaround. Forcing pseudo-terminal allocation allows me to run fish+starship with ssh.\n> \n> ```\n> ssh -t desktop fish \n> ```\n> \n> or if you add `RequestTTY force` to ssh_config it will work without `-t`\n> \n> ```\n> Host desktop\n>   User osbm\n>   HostName 192.168.0.1\n>   IdentityFile [identity file path]\n>   RemoteCommand fish\n>   RequestTTY force\n> ```\n\nI would've tried it but the command works for me now :D, idk check what version are you running.\nmine is:\n```\nrsync  version 3.4.1  protocol version 32\nstarship 1.21.1\nfish, version 3.7.1\nkitty 0.37.0 created by Kovid Goyal\n```\n",
